      • getFeatures

        protected java.util.List<java.lang.String> getFeatures()
        Get a list of the chado/so types of the SequenceFeatures we wish to load. The list will not include chromosome-like features (eg. "chromosome" and "chromosome_arm"). The process methods will ignore features that are not in this list.
        Returns:
        the list of features

      • getSegmentedFeatures

        protected java.util.List<java.lang.String> getSegmentedFeatures()
        Return a list of types where one logical feature is represented as multiple rows in the feature table. An example is UTR features in flybase - if a UTR spans multiple exons, each part is a separate row in the feature table. In InterMine we represent the UTR as a single object with a start and end so we need special handling for these types.
        Returns:
        a list of segmented feature type

      • getExtraFeatureConstraint

        protected java.lang.String getExtraFeatureConstraint()
        Return an extra constraint to be used when querying the feature table. Any feature table column or cvterm table column can be constrained. The cvterm will match the type_id field in the feature. eg. "uniquename not like 'BAD_ID%'"
        Returns:
        the constraint as SQL or nul if there is no extra constraint.

      • getFeatureRelationshipResultSet

        protected java.sql.ResultSet getFeatureRelationshipResultSet(java.sql.Connection connection,
                                                 boolean subjectFirst)
                                                      throws java.sql.SQLException
        Return the interesting rows from the feature_relationship table. The feature pairs are returned in both subject, object and object, subject orientations so that the relationship processing can be configured in a natural way. This is a protected method so that it can be overridden for testing
        Parameters:
        connection - the db connection
        subjectFirst - if true the subject_id column from the relationship table will be before the object_id in the results, otherwise it will be after. ie. "feature_relationship_id, subject_id as feature1_id, object_id as feature2_id, ..." vs "feature_relationship_id, object_id as feature1_id, subject_id as feature2_id, ..."
        Returns:
        the SQL result set
        Throws:
        java.sql.SQLException - if a database problem occurs
